listings.episode_description: Rosie volunteers to put Iggy to bed, but she has to follow his special routine; Rosie assists Crystal in her magic show.

Bert and Ernie, Oscar the Grouch and Grover are just a few of the other creatures involved in this show, set on a city street full of valuable learning opportunities.
listings.episode_description: Prairie Dawn is hosting a cookie party where all the cookies are baked in all kinds of shapes; Cookie Monster is excited to eat all the octagon shaped cookies but needs to figure out which of the cookies are octagons.

listings.description: Opera lovers, rejoice! If you can't make it to New York to see a performance at the Metropolitan Opera, the next best thing to being there is to see one of its Saturday matinees broadcast on PBS. Originally aired as part of its "Great Performances" series, the programs got their own title in 2006. With operatic standards like "Aida," "The Barber of Seville" and "Turandot," and performances by some of opera's biggest names, including Reneé Flemming, Placido Domingo and Anna Netrebko, the series brings the best of modern opera into American homes.

listings.title: Great Performances at the Met
listings.description: Opera lovers, rejoice! If you can't make it to New York to see a performance at the Metropolitan Opera, the next best thing to being there is to see one of its Saturday matinees broadcast on PBS. Originally aired as part of its "Great Performances" series, the programs got their own title in 2006. With operatic standards like "Aida," "The Barber of Seville" and "Turandot," and performances by some of opera's biggest names, including Reneé Flemming, Placido Domingo and Anna Netrebko, the series brings the best of modern opera into American homes.

listings.title: Eyes on the Prize
listings.description: This landmark series, which first premiered in 1987, documents the history of the civil rights movement in America. Produced by Blackside, segments include the Montgomery bus boycott of 1954, school desegregation in 1957 Arkansas, the right-to-vote battle within Mississippi, the march from Selma to Montgomery, Ala., and the Voting Rights Act of 1965. The series has been honored with a George Foster Peabody Award, an International Documentary Award, Television Critics Association Award and numerous Emmy Awards.

Will Davenport. Geordie forms an unlikely partnership with both men of the cloth, and as partners they bring different insights into the crimes they start to unravel, forming true friendships as they work together. Village life in Grantchester proves to be much livelier than its sleepy appearance might suggest, with intrigue and gossip swirling in the background of Geordie's investigations.
listings.episode_description: Will and Geordie's much-needed vacation takes an unexpected turn when the camp owner is found dead under suspicious circumstances.

listings.description: Opera lovers, rejoice! If you can't make it to New York to see a performance at the Metropolitan Opera, the next best thing to being there is to see one of its Saturday matinees broadcast on PBS. Originally aired as part of its "Great Performances" series, the programs got their own title in 2006. With operatic standards like "Aida," "The Barber of Seville" and "Turandot," and performances by some of opera's biggest names, including Reneé Flemming, Placido Domingo and Anna Netrebko, the series brings the best of modern opera into American homes.

listings.description: Yoga can be challenging, especially for beginners who may be apprehensive about trying something that they think is too daunting. Wanting to help those who are new to the exercise, fitness instructor Sarah Starr created an easier routine. Happy Yoga, as she calls it, is a modified program using chairs that allows people of any age or physical condition to be able to benefit from yoga. "Happy Yoga" features Starr performing the chair exercises outside, utilizing serene backdrops that showcase Mother Nature's beauty.
listings.episode_description: A creative flow practice designed to open more space and ease in the shoulders, chest and upper back.

In the show, the animated Kratts encounter wild animals during stories of adventure and mystery. The live-action Kratt brothers introduce each episode.
listings.episode_description: The Kratt brothers search for a mysterious nocturnal creature, using night-vision goggles.

listings.episode_description: Lyla overcomes her fear of rock-climbing; a riddle game about everyday objects made by Black inventors.

listings.title: Fons & Porter's Love of Quilting
listings.description: Hosts Sara Gallegos and Angela Huffman work with guests to explore quilting ideas, both old and new, in this series from Iowa Public Television. Whether a beginner or an expert, quilters of all levels will learn something from the tips, techniques and designs featured on this show. Segments from the series include two quilts that feature a diagonally set log cabin design, a small quilt constructed with English paper piecing, a breakdown of a medallion-style quilt into simple lessons, and how to resize a quilt block into larger and smaller versions.
listings.episode_description: A two-block quilt featuring half-square triangles and strip sets; a method for creating bias binding.

listings.title: Fit 2 Stitch
listings.description: Concentrating on design, fit and stitching, this series hosted by Peggy Sagers offers sewing tips for anyone who has a desire to fit and sew clothing. Episodes focus on the rules of making patterns and how they apply to preparing a garment for stitching. Projects range from ones that require just a single stitch to more elaborate items such as pants, sleeves, tank tops and wrap dresses. Other segments include how to make a cape, use zippers and sew a half-circle skirt.
listings.episode_description: Making professional alterations on a pair of men's pants; shortening a sleeve.

listings.title: Samantha Brown's Places to Love
listings.description: Samantha Brown explores the emotional heart of travel and the people who change, challenge and strengthen a destination.
listings.episode_description: St. Louis Arch; Ted Drewes Frozen Custard; author Michael Wallis offers insights on Route 66; Osage Trail Legacy monument; Uranus Fudge Factory; Gearhead Curios; Buck Atom's Cosmic Curios.

listings.title: The Daytripper
listings.description: This six-time Emmy Award-winning travel series centers on one-day adventures exploring the food, culture and history of Texas towns. From Abilene to Wimberley, host Chet Garner covers well-known landmarks as well as obscure dives and hideaways all throughout the Lone Star state. Some destinations include the National Museum of the Pacific War in Fredericksburg; Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth; a mountaintop classroom in Alpine, Texas; Big Bend National Park; and a visit to the oldest deli in Texas.
listings.episode_description: The history of the springs in West Texas; two museums, including one that trained World War II bombardiers; burritos and steak; exploring Hotel Settles.

listings.title: Outside: Beyond the Lens

listings.episode_description: Unique landscapes in Utah's remote Cottonwood Canyon State Park.

listings.title: Rick Steves' Europe

listings.description: Rick Steves' guidebooks, public-radio program and numerous television series have made him an essential resource for travelers wishing to explore Europe. This program finds the knowledgeable host offering globetrotters a fresh perspective on lodgings, transportation and places to visit on their journeys. One thing that hasn't changed, however, is Steves' belief that travelers should become "temporary locals," exploring not only major cities and the usual sites, but out-of-the-way locales that often produce the most authentic, and enjoyable, experiences of a trip.
listings.episode_description: Exploring ancient Roman cities from England to Turkey, including their art, aqueducts, theaters and churches.

The cast includes host Kevin O'Connor, general contractor Tom Silva, heating/plumbing master Richard Trethewey and landscaper Roger Cook, who spend the hour focusing on various topics for the do-it-yourself homeowner.
listings.episode_description: Painting stair treads and handrail; highlighting new tools; installing new wall sconces above a fireplace.

listings.title: America's Test Kitchen From Cook's Illustrated
listings.description: Bridget Lancaster and Julia Collin Davison host a look inside America's Test Kitchen, which features a team of experts who check out the latest in cooking utensils, ingredients and cooking techniques. Whether they're trying to make the perfect roasted chicken with crispy skin or examining the science behind cooking with baking powder, team members try to offer unbiased and useful tips that can save viewers money, time and effort in their own kitchens. The basic team is frequently joined by other test cooks, as well as blind-taste judges.
listings.episode_description: Indoor pulled chicken; basmati rice; gadgets; flaky buttermilk biscuits.

listings.title: Cook's Country
listings.description: Hosts Bridget Lancaster and Julia Collin Davison offer a practical, no-nonsense and scientific approach to making a wide range of American recipes, from barbecue chicken thighs to Mississippi mud pie to parmesan potatoes. The hosts are joined by test cooks Ashley Moore, Bryan Roof, Christie Morrison, Lawman Johnson, and Natalie Estrada. Episodes include equipment recommendations for the home cook, taste tests and origins for new recipes such as Southern-style smothered chicken, grilled bourbon steaks and many more.
listings.episode_description: Cheesy stuffed shells; 13x9 broiler-safe baking dishes; eggplant pecorino.

listings.title: Lidia's Kitchen

With tips and techniques collected over the years, Lidia prepares everything from apple cider-braised pork shoulder and salmon with mustard sauce to lentil country salad and Grandma Rosa's apple cake. Lidia's passion for cooking shines in every episode, where she teaches viewers how to draw on their own roots to create a sense of home in the kitchen.
listings.episode_description: Fried panzerotti; ricotta soup; gnocchi with sauce from Erice.

Each episode features a single Mexican food, ranging from familiar ingredients like vanilla to mysterious grains used by the Aztecs. Season 8 explores simple and delectable dishes from both Mexico and the United States, including street food, a seafood feast, taco recipes, lobster recipes, and a breakfast based on Sinaloan classics.
listings.episode_description: Exploring Campeche, Mexico, a colonial city defined by its history of piracy; turkey panuchos; La Pigua features regional dishes pescado verde and grilled octopus.

listings.description: Chef, cookbook author and TV host Sara Moulton presents helpful hints for preparing quick and easy healthy meals at home. Episodes feature ideas for Sunday suppers, for one-pot meals, and for preparing flavor-packed meals using only five ingredients. Some recipes include pork tournedos with sage and prosciutto, steamed mussels in curried coconut broth, a fried-catfish bacon/lettuce/tomato sandwich, and a salad of grilled-salmon, arugula and grilled corn.
listings.episode_description: Chicken paillard; baked chicken thighs with artichoke hearts and homemade lemon pickles; a simple galette of ham and eggs wrapped in pastry.

listings.description: Hyacinth Bucket (pronounced Bouquet, if you please) lives to impress. And she has no patience for people who pretend to be superior -- because that makes it "so much harder for those of us who really are." Assured of her own eminence, she spends her days trying to make sure everyone else is, too. Her down-market sisters, Rose and Daisy, are a challenge, but she's always willing to talk about her rich sister Violet. Violet's eccentric, cross-dressing husband, not so much.
listings.episode_description: When Hyacinth invites the new vicar to tea, she organizes the event down to the last sugar cube.

His latest assistant is Detective Sergeant Jamie Winter. DCI Barnaby took over in series 14, replacing his older cousin, Chief Inspector Tom Barnaby, who retired.

Each week, Marcus visits a new city to learn about how that city made its mark. Featuring musicians, poets, chefs, business owners, artists, community leaders and home cooks, the program spotlights people who have enhanced the nation's culture and cuisine. Some segments include the sights and sounds of Detroit's Arab-American community, how Vietnamese cuisine and culture have influenced New Orleans, and the flavors and heritage of the Haitian community in Miami.

listings.title: The Best of the Joy of Painting
listings.description: This series of episodes culled from the vast library of the late Bob Ross ("The Joy of Painting") features the soft-spoken host sharing his painting techniques, including his "wet-on-wet" technique, and creating some of his best-loved scenes. From a cabin in the majestic mountains or a covered bride to an owl in a country barn or an autumnal forest scene, Ross creates a complete work of art in each episode -- many of which feature his trademark "happy little clouds." His soothing tone and words of encouragement inspire those painting along at home, and entrance those just watching to see him create his nature scenes.
listings.episode_description: A seascape features gentle waves caressing the shoreline.

With operatic standards like "Aida," "The Barber of Seville" and "Turandot," and performances by some of opera's biggest names, including Reneé Flemming, Placido Domingo and Anna Netrebko, the series brings the best of modern opera into American homes.
listings.episode_description: Mezzo-soprano Emily D'Angelo portrays Jess, a fighter pilot whose unplanned pregnancy takes her out of the cockpit and lands her in Las Vegas, operating a drone.

listings.title: Father Brown
listings.description: Based on the novels of G.K. Chesterton.
listings.episode_description: When a troubled soul from the past returns, Father Brown must investigate the new chapter of the Church of Apollo.

listings.title: On the Record
listings.description: Interviews with key players in San Antonio politics, business, and community activism. Each week also includes a roundtable discussion with local journalists who keep a pulse on important issues impacting the city.
listings.episode_description: Interviews with key players in San Antonio politics, business, and community activism. Each week also includes a roundtable discussion with local journalists who keep a pulse on important issues impacting the city.

listings.title: Happy Yoga With Sarah Starr
listings.description: Yoga can be challenging, especially for beginners who may be apprehensive about trying something that they think is too daunting. Wanting to help those who are new to the exercise, fitness instructor Sarah Starr created an easier routine. Happy Yoga, as she calls it, is a modified program using chairs that allows people of any age or physical condition to be able to benefit from yoga. "Happy Yoga" features Starr performing the chair exercises outside, utilizing serene backdrops that showcase Mother Nature's beauty.
listings.episode_description: A creative flow practice designed to open more space and ease in the shoulders, chest and upper back.

listings.title: Classical Stretch: By Essentrics
listings.description: Miranda Esmonde-White offers an exercise program for people of all ages and fitness levels.
listings.episode_description: An all-standing workout aimed at strengthening the abs and waist; from Playa del Carmen, Mexico.

listings.title: Wild Kratts
listings.description: This show follows the adventures of animated versions of brothers Chris and Martin Kratt, hosts of such educational shows as "Kratts' Creatures" and "Zoboomafoo." In the show, the animated Kratts encounter wild animals during stories of adventure and mystery. The live-action Kratt brothers introduce each episode.
listings.episode_description: The Kratt brothers search for a mysterious nocturnal creature, using night-vision goggles.

listings.title: Alma's Way
listings.description: Six-year old Alma, a Puerto Rican girl who lives with her family in the Bronx, learns to think for herself, making mistakes and finding solutions along the way.
listings.episode_description: Alma helps Mr. Ramirez figure out what to do when he lets too many cats into his shoe shop; Alma tries to convince Howard to play stickball.

listings.title: Lyla in the Loop
listings.episode_title: Lyla Gets a Grip; Rappin' Riddles
listings.description: Seven-year-old Lyla and her close-knit family address everyday problems together in the big city.
listings.episode_description: Lyla overcomes her fear of rock-climbing; a riddle game about everyday objects made by Black inventors.

listings.title: Carl the Collector
listings.episode_title: The Remote Control Collection; The Super Blue Moon Sleepover
listings.description: The everyday adventures of Carl, an autistic raccoon, who loves collecting things.
listings.episode_description: Forrest can't wait to try everything at the Fuzzytown Friends Picnic, but gets into trouble when he is unable to wait his turn; Carl hosts a Super Blue Moon Sleepover.

listings.title: Fons & Porter's Love of Quilting
listings.description: Hosts Sara Gallegos and Angela Huffman work with guests to explore quilting ideas, both old and new, in this series from Iowa Public Television. Whether a beginner or an expert, quilters of all levels will learn something from the tips, techniques and designs featured on this show. Segments from the series include two quilts that feature a diagonally set log cabin design, a small quilt constructed with English paper piecing, a breakdown of a medallion-style quilt into simple lessons, and how to resize a quilt block into larger and smaller versions.
listings.episode_description: A two-block quilt featuring half-square triangles and strip sets; a method for creating bias binding.

listings.title: Fit 2 Stitch
listings.description: Concentrating on design, fit and stitching, this series hosted by Peggy Sagers offers sewing tips for anyone who has a desire to fit and sew clothing. Episodes focus on the rules of making patterns and how they apply to preparing a garment for stitching. Projects range from ones that require just a single stitch to more elaborate items such as pants, sleeves, tank tops and wrap dresses. Other segments include how to make a cape, use zippers and sew a half-circle skirt.
listings.episode_description: Making professional alterations on a pair of men's pants; shortening a sleeve.

listings.title: Samantha Brown's Places to Love
listings.description: Samantha Brown explores the emotional heart of travel and the people who change, challenge and strengthen a destination.
listings.episode_description: St. Louis Arch; Ted Drewes Frozen Custard; author Michael Wallis offers insights on Route 66; Osage Trail Legacy monument; Uranus Fudge Factory; Gearhead Curios; Buck Atom's Cosmic Curios.

listings.title: The Daytripper
listings.description: This six-time Emmy Award-winning travel series centers on one-day adventures exploring the food, culture and history of Texas towns. From Abilene to Wimberley, host Chet Garner covers well-known landmarks as well as obscure dives and hideaways all throughout the Lone Star state. Some destinations include the National Museum of the Pacific War in Fredericksburg; Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth; a mountaintop classroom in Alpine, Texas; Big Bend National Park; and a visit to the oldest deli in Texas.
listings.episode_description: The history of the springs in West Texas; two museums, including one that trained World War II bombardiers; burritos and steak; exploring Hotel Settles.

listings.title: Outside: Beyond the Lens
listings.description: Exploring America's national parks and scenic wonders around the world.
listings.episode_description: Unique landscapes in Utah's remote Cottonwood Canyon State Park.

listings.title: Rick Steves' Europe
listings.episode_title: Rick Steves' Europe: Art of the Roman Empire
listings.description: Rick Steves' guidebooks, public-radio program and numerous television series have made him an essential resource for travelers wishing to explore Europe. This program finds the knowledgeable host offering globetrotters a fresh perspective on lodgings, transportation and places to visit on their journeys. One thing that hasn't changed, however, is Steves' belief that travelers should become "temporary locals," exploring not only major cities and the usual sites, but out-of-the-way locales that often produce the most authentic, and enjoyable, experiences of a trip.
listings.episode_description: Exploring ancient Roman cities from England to Turkey, including their art, aqueducts, theaters and churches.

listings.title: Christopher Kimball's Milk Street Television
listings.description: Christopher Kimball demonstrates a bolder yet simpler way of preparing food.
listings.episode_description: Hungarian chicken paprikash with dumplings and cucumber salad; learning about the paprika farmers of Budapest; Hungarian goulash.

listings.title: Milk Street's My Family Recipe
listings.description: With a combination of historical context and modern culinary know-how, chefs Christopher Kimball and Cheryl Day help home cooks recreate lost or forgotten cherished family recipes.
listings.episode_description: Melissa Long's Czech friend Tatiana sometimes prepared a rustic pork, sausage and sauerkraut soup; Milk Street wants to add their own spin on it.

listings.title: Christina Cooks: Back to the Cutting Board
listings.episode_title: Cook Your Way to the Life You Want
listings.description: Healthy, fresh Italian and Mediterranean recipes from Christina Pirello.
listings.episode_description: Wise guy chili; brown rice and millet croquettes; cannoli napoleon; whole-grains; ways that sugar is hidden in products; snack ideas.

listings.title: The Key Ingredient with Sheri Castle
listings.description: Sheri Castle offers favorite recipes from her kitchen and the stories behind featured ingredients.
listings.episode_description: Candied jalapeno cheese ball; a warm stew of roasted green chili, chicken and white beans; roasting peppers; growing hot peppers in the south; cooking with Von Diaz.

listings.title: This Old House
listings.episode_title: Ridgewood: Colonial Revival With Modern Flair
listings.description: This Emmy-winning home-improvement series takes the mystery and fright factors out of remodeling and carpentry chores.
listings.episode_description: The renovation of the 1930s colonial revival wraps up; a tour of the house reveals the new back extension and patio with water feature; the location of the next project is revealed.

listings.title: Ask This Old House
listings.description: Created by viewer demand, the series is a spinoff of "This Old House" and answers specific remodeling questions that viewers send in. The cast includes host Kevin O'Connor, general contractor Tom Silva, heating/plumbing master Richard Trethewey and landscaper Roger Cook, who spend the hour focusing on various topics for the do-it-yourself homeowner.
listings.episode_description: Painting stair treads and handrail; highlighting new tools; installing new wall sconces above a fireplace.

listings.title: America's Test Kitchen From Cook's Illustrated
listings.description: Bridget Lancaster and Julia Collin Davison host a look inside America's Test Kitchen, which features a team of experts who check out the latest in cooking utensils, ingredients and cooking techniques. Whether they're trying to make the perfect roasted chicken with crispy skin or examining the science behind cooking with baking powder, team members try to offer unbiased and useful tips that can save viewers money, time and effort in their own kitchens. The basic team is frequently joined by other test cooks, as well as blind-taste judges.
listings.episode_description: Indoor pulled chicken; basmati rice; gadgets; flaky buttermilk biscuits.

listings.title: Cook's Country
listings.description: Hosts Bridget Lancaster and Julia Collin Davison offer a practical, no-nonsense and scientific approach to making a wide range of American recipes, from barbecue chicken thighs to Mississippi mud pie to parmesan potatoes. The hosts are joined by test cooks Ashley Moore, Bryan Roof, Christie Morrison, Lawman Johnson, and Natalie Estrada. Episodes include equipment recommendations for the home cook, taste tests and origins for new recipes such as Southern-style smothered chicken, grilled bourbon steaks and many more.
listings.episode_description: Cheesy stuffed shells; 13x9 broiler-safe baking dishes; eggplant pecorino.

listings.title: Lidia's Kitchen
listings.description: Daytime Emmy-winning chef Lidia Bastianich prepares simple, seasonal and economical dishes in this 26-episode series presented by WGBH. With tips and techniques collected over the years, Lidia prepares everything from apple cider-braised pork shoulder and salmon with mustard sauce to lentil country salad and Grandma Rosa's apple cake. Lidia's passion for cooking shines in every episode, where she teaches viewers how to draw on their own roots to create a sense of home in the kitchen.
listings.episode_description: Fried panzerotti; ricotta soup; gnocchi with sauce from Erice.

listings.title: Pati's Mexican Table
listings.episode_title: Campeche -- Tale of a Pirate City
listings.description: Chef Pati Jinich introduces authentic Mexican flavors, colors and textures into American kitchens. Each episode features a single Mexican food, ranging from familiar ingredients like vanilla to mysterious grains used by the Aztecs. Season 8 explores simple and delectable dishes from both Mexico and the United States, including street food, a seafood feast, taco recipes, lobster recipes, and a breakfast based on Sinaloan classics.
listings.episode_description: Exploring Campeche, Mexico, a colonial city defined by its history of piracy; turkey panuchos; La Pigua features regional dishes pescado verde and grilled octopus.

listings.title: Sara's Weeknight Meals
listings.description: Chef, cookbook author and TV host Sara Moulton presents helpful hints for preparing quick and easy healthy meals at home. Episodes feature ideas for Sunday suppers, for one-pot meals, and for preparing flavor-packed meals using only five ingredients. Some recipes include pork tournedos with sage and prosciutto, steamed mussels in curried coconut broth, a fried-catfish bacon/lettuce/tomato sandwich, and a salad of grilled-salmon, arugula and grilled corn.
listings.episode_description: Chicken paillard; baked chicken thighs with artichoke hearts and homemade lemon pickles; a simple galette of ham and eggs wrapped in pastry.

listings.title: Samantha Brown's Places to Love
listings.description: Samantha Brown explores the emotional heart of travel and the people who change, challenge and strengthen a destination.
listings.episode_description: St. Louis Arch; Ted Drewes Frozen Custard; author Michael Wallis offers insights on Route 66; Osage Trail Legacy monument; Uranus Fudge Factory; Gearhead Curios; Buck Atom's Cosmic Curios.

listings.title: PBS News Weekend
listings.description: Analysis of national and international news, as well as in-depth reporting on topics ranging from education and politics to technology and finance.
listings.episode_description: Analysis of national and international news, as well as in-depth reporting on topics ranging from education and politics to technology and finance.

listings.description: Based on the novels of G.K. Chesterton.
listings.episode_description: When a troubled soul from the past returns, Father Brown must investigate the new chapter of the Church of Apollo.

listings.title: Keeping Up Appearances
listings.description: Hyacinth Bucket (pronounced Bouquet, if you please) lives to impress. And she has no patience for people who pretend to be superior -- because that makes it "so much harder for those of us who really are." Assured of her own eminence, she spends her days trying to make sure everyone else is, too. Her down-market sisters, Rose and Daisy, are a challenge, but she's always willing to talk about her rich sister Violet. Violet's eccentric, cross-dressing husband, not so much.
listings.episode_description: When Hyacinth invites the new vicar to tea, she organizes the event down to the last sugar cube.

listings.title: Midsomer Murders
listings.description: Based on the crime-novel series by author Caroline Graham, "Midsomer Murders" follows the efforts of Detective Chief Inspector John Barnaby to solve crimes that occur in the wealthy, isolated English county of Midsomer, a picturesque and peaceful place on the outside but one filled with amoral and snobbish eccentrics with all kinds of vices. His latest assistant is Detective Sergeant Jamie Winter. DCI Barnaby took over in series 14, replacing his older cousin, Chief Inspector Tom Barnaby, who retired.
listings.episode_description: A woman is found strangled nine years after three identical murders took place in the same area.

listings.episode_description: Long-buried memories are raked up for J.P. when someone from his past is caught at a murder scene, and Jack must unravel a complex mystery to find the truth.

listings.episode_title: Jelly Roll; The War and Treaty

Originally created to shine a spotlight on original Texas music, the show has expanded its boundaries to encompass a wide range of styles and artists, featuring notables such as Pearl Jam, Elvis Costello, Johnny Cash and Neil Young.
listings.episode_description: Jelly Roll performs highlights from "Whitsitt Chapel"; husband-and-wife duo The War and Treaty.

listings.episode_description: Rae must remember the buttons to push to get the Beeples to Marshmallow Mountain Station when she takes a job as a train engineer; Dev needs to stay organized.

listings.title: Skillsville
listings.description: Three curious kids explore the world of video games and career possibilities.
listings.episode_description: The kids offer to help Cora's mom by becoming Skillsville Game Testers; Rae takes on the role of an interior designer.

listings.title: Skillsville
listings.description: Three curious kids explore the world of video games and career possibilities.
listings.episode_description: Dev works on a movie as a sound effects artist; Cora becomes a city planner to create a new area in Skillsville that everyone can enjoy.

listings.episode_description: Dev needs to stay organized as a laundromat manager to clean the team jerseys; Rae creates an easier way for the Beeples to get to the top of Mount Froyo.

listings.title: Skillsville
listings.description: Three curious kids explore the world of video games and career possibilities.
listings.episode_description: Firefighter Rae uses a strategy to remain calm as she helps save the farm; as a bank teller, Cora needs to stay focused when helping the Beeples with depositing and withdrawing from their accounts.

listings.description: This show follows the adventures of animated versions of brothers Chris and Martin Kratt, hosts of such educational shows as "Kratts' Creatures" and "Zoboomafoo." In the show, the animated Kratts encounter wild animals during stories of adventure and mystery. The live-action Kratt brothers introduce each episode.
listings.episode_description: The Wild Kratts set off to find and re-create spider silk.

listings.title: Wild Kratts
listings.description: This show follows the adventures of animated versions of brothers Chris and Martin Kratt, hosts of such educational shows as "Kratts' Creatures" and "Zoboomafoo." In the show, the animated Kratts encounter wild animals during stories of adventure and mystery. The live-action Kratt brothers introduce each episode.

listings.title: Odd Squad
listings.episode_title: Teach A Man to Ice Fish
listings.description: Young government agents Olive and Otto use math to investigate strange occurrences in their town. Produced by The Fred Rogers Co., this live-action series targets preschool and early elementary schoolchildren and their families. Odd Squad cases include disappearing zeroes, Santa's missing reindeer, runaway dinosaurs, and characters who escape from books. Throughout the series, Olive and Otto learn not only how to solve problems but also about working together, communication and perseverance.
listings.episode_description: When villain Confetti Betty strikes the Odd Squad headquarters in the Arctic, the Mobile Unit return to help; as they attempt to crack the villain's pattern, they must teach the agents how to solve cases for themselves.

listings.title: Arthur
listings.episode_title: D.W. Aims High; Flaw and Order
listings.description: Bespectacled aardvark Arthur Read demonstrates to kids how to deal with such childhood traumas and challenges as homework, teachers and bullies. He also has to contend with his sisters, but loves playing with his friends: tomboy Francine, foodie and best pal Buster, supersmart Brain, rich girl Muffy and geography expert Sue Ellen.
listings.episode_description: D.W. wants to be the first person on Mars but fears there may be aliens; Arthur takes the blame for cracking Dad's cake platter.

listings.title: The Cat in the Hat Knows a Lot About That!
listings.episode_title: Step This Way; Anything You Can Do
listings.description: Martin Short provides the voice of the title character in this animated series from PBS Kids, which aims to promote children's literacy in science. It follows the magical adventures of 6-year-olds Nick and Sally, who travel the world with the Cat in the Hat as their guide. As they travel in the Cat's customized vehicle, the Thinga-ma-jigger, which can float, fly, drive and even ski, they learn about natural science, visiting the rainforest, the bottom of the sea, and all places in between. They're joined in their travels by the Cat's mop-headed sidekicks, Thing One and Thing Two.
listings.episode_description: Sally and Nick learn about feet while playing dress up; Nick and Sally pretend to be The Cat.

listings.title: Dinosaur Train
listings.description: Preschoolers get to hop on board the Dinosaur Train to learn about natural science, natural history and paleontology. Each half-hour episode of this series, produced in CGI-animated format by the Jim Henson Company, features Buddy, a preschool-aged Tyrannosaurus Rex, and his adoptive Pteranodon family traveling on a special train to meet all kinds of dinosaurs and explore the world inhabited by these amazing creatures. Also included are live-action segments hosted by paleontologist Scott Sampson.
listings.episode_description: Mr. Pteranodon is annoyed when the new neighbor moves in; a day trip to the Big Pond.

listings.title: Pinkalicious & Peterrific
listings.description: The creative adventures of Pinkalicious and her brother, Peter.
listings.episode_description: Pinkalicious and Peter decide to put on their own show after Jonah Rose's concert sells out; Pinkalicious writes a catchy song.

listings.title: Peg + Cat
listings.episode_title: The Blockette Problem; The Tulip Problem
listings.description: The Fred Rogers Company introduces a new animated preschool series featuring Peg and her sidekick, Cat, as they encounter unexpected challenges that require arithmetic and problem-solving skills. Each episode features two stories in which Peg and Cat face a math word problem that they must solve. Children will learn how to build calculation skills and think about larger concepts that will help them form the foundation for learning math at any level, from kindergarten through calculus.
listings.episode_description: Peg and Cat work on the set for the Radio City Music Hall Blockettes; Peg and Cat settle a tiff between two neighbors by giving them flowers.

listings.title: Sesame Street
listings.description: A longtime favorite of children and adults, and a staple of PBS, "Sesame Street" bridges many cultural and educational gaps with a fun program. Big Bird leads a cast of characters teaching children numbers, colors and the alphabet. Bert and Ernie, Oscar the Grouch and Grover are just a few of the other creatures involved in this show, set on a city street full of valuable learning opportunities.
listings.episode_description: Tamir leaves for robotics camp; he needs to figure out how to keep the garden watered while he is away; with help from his friends, Tamir makes a drip irrigation system so that the community garden can get plenty of water.

listings.title: Milo
listings.description: A young cat, Milo, lives with his parents at their drycleaner; their robotic washing machine, Suds, lets Milo and his friends try on different outfits, introducing them to a realm of endless possibilities.
listings.episode_description: Inspired by dancers Eleanor and Mycroft, Milo, Lofty and Lark are transported to the stage of the Dance Theatre; but when they have to step in to perform at the show, they must overcome their stage fright if they are to deliver a Dance Spectacular.

listings.title: Work It Out Wombats!
listings.episode_title: A Boxful of Snout; Postcard From Snout
listings.description: A playful trio of marsupial siblings look for interesting problems to solve in their Treeborhood.
listings.episode_description: The Wombats lose Snout while helping Mr. E wrap boxes; Snout sends a postcard to Zeke.

listings.title: Work It Out Wombats!
listings.episode_title: The Great Splendito; The Bike Wash
listings.description: A playful trio of marsupial siblings look for interesting problems to solve in their Treeborhood.
listings.episode_description: The search for Mr. Splendito tickets is on; the Wombats power-clean a bunch of bikes.

listings.title: Daniel Tiger's Neighborhood
listings.episode_title: Friends Help Each Other; Daniel Helps O Tell a Story
listings.description: The first series inspired by "Mister Rogers Neighborhood," "Daniel Tiger's Neighborhood" features 4-year-old Daniel Tiger, son of the original program's Daniel Striped Tiger. Every day Daniel puts on his red sweater, ties his shoes, and invites a new generation of preschoolers into the Neighborhood of Make-Believe. Daniel shares his daily adventures with pals O the Owl, Katerina Kittycat, Prince Wednesday and Miss Elaina. With the help of Daniel and his friends, preschoolers have fun and learn practical skills necessary for growing and developing.
listings.episode_description: Daniel helps Katerina reassemble her tea set after it is knocked on the floor; Daniel helps finish a story about dinosaurs.

listings.title: Daniel Tiger's Neighborhood

Every day Daniel puts on his red sweater, ties his shoes, and invites a new generation of preschoolers into the Neighborhood of Make-Believe. Daniel shares his daily adventures with pals O the Owl, Katerina Kittycat, Prince Wednesday and Miss Elaina. listings.episode_description: Daniel and Miss Elaine play outer space; Daniel is sad when Prince Wednesday tells him his rock collection is too delicate to play with.

listings.title: Carl the Collector
listings.episode_title: The Plushie Collection; The Bouncy Ball Collection
listings.description: The everyday adventures of Carl, an autistic raccoon, who loves collecting things.
listings.episode_description: Carl turns to his friends to help him organize his plushie collection; Carl loses his bouncy ball collection.

listings.title: Curious George
listings.description: Curious George is a sweet African monkey who can't help but run into trouble. George's friend, "The Man in the Yellow Hat," tries very hard to care for George and is always saving the day. The show's themes are about learning, forgiveness and playful curiosity.
listings.episode_description: George, Allie, Bill and Vicki learn the ways different animals swim to then compete in a swimming race in the pond to win a treat; when George visits a museum exhibit about Thomas Edison, he gets inspired to make his own "Museum of George."

listings.title: Donkey Hodie
listings.description: Donkey Hodie and her pals follow their dreams and work together to find creative solutions to everyday problems.
listings.episode_description: Donkey wants to make Grampy a surprise birthday breakfast but none of her flapjacks will fly; Panda's toy pickle gets stuck between two rocks.

listings.title: Donkey Hodie
listings.episode_title: Me, Myself, and Donkey; Fashion Donkey
listings.description: Donkey Hodie and her pals follow their dreams and work together to find creative solutions to everyday problems.
listings.episode_description: Donkey is disappointed when her friends are away for the day but finds a way to have fun on her own; Donkey wants to be like Fashion Penguin.

listings.description: The adventures of an observant and curious bunny rabbit named Elinor and her friends Ari the bat and Olive the elephant.

The characters live in Storybook Village, which is accessible through a panel that is represented by an invisible question mark. Preschool children follow the Super Readers as they jump into books that come to life.

Produced by Blackside, segments include the Montgomery bus boycott of 1954, school desegregation in 1957 Arkansas, the right-to-vote battle within Mississippi, the march from Selma to Montgomery, Ala., and the Voting Rights Act of 1965. The series has been honored with a George Foster Peabody Award, an International Documentary Award, Television Critics Association Award and numerous Emmy Awards.
listings.episode_description: Antidiscrimination legal rights are tested during the 1970s as Bostonians violently resist a federal court school desegregation order; Maynard Jackson becomes Atlanta's mayor.

The historical drama follows the story of Thomas Cromwell through his rise in social hierarchy. From his humble beginnings as a blacksmith's son, Cromwell becomes King Henry VIII's chief minister. The episodes chronicle his life as he deals with the power struggles of the Tudor Court and a king who has difficulty producing a male heir.

Basing her healthy meals and snacks on traditional American cuisine, Laura prepares recipes without dairy, meat, eggs or animal products. From festive zucchini lasagna to chocolate desserts, Laura's recipes are also cholesterol-free. Other dishes include sunflower avocado rolls, pasta with broccoli and sun-dried tomatoes, oven-baked Moroccan stew and apple muffins with pumpkin seeds.

listings.description: This six-episode series hosted by chef Marcus Samuelsson offers viewers a culinary and anthropological exploration of the people, rituals and food of multicultural America. Each week, Marcus visits a new city to learn about how that city made its mark. Whether it's a bittersweet chocolate ganache, from which he creates souffle cakes and an Asian banana split, or flavorful chicken broth he then uses to prepare ginger-poached chicken breast and hot and sour shrimp soup, the chef shares recipes and tricks for the beginning cook as well as the accomplished kitchen pro.

listings.episode_description: A Sumo wrestler puts on an exhibition match with Luna after Salami Strong gets injured; Leo overcomes his fear of Lizardzilla movies.

listings.title: Rosie's Rules
listings.description: Five-year-old Mexican American Rosie Fuentes learns how the world around her works in her suburban Texas community.
listings.episode_description: Rosie and Javi prepare for the arrival of a dragon; Rosie finds a lucky charm in the backyard.

listings.title: Xavier Riddle and the Secret Museum
listings.episode_title: I Am Hedy Lamarr; I Am Archimedes
listings.description: Xavier Riddle, his sister, Yadina, and their friend, Brad, meet heroes from the past -- from Eleanor Roosevelt to Leonardo da Vinci.
listings.episode_description: Hedy Lamarr shows Yadina that she can do more than one thing; Xavier, Yadina and Brad learn that creative thinking can lead to new ideas.

listings.title: Alma's Way
listings.episode_title: A Tale of Two Almas; The Longest Race
listings.description: Six-year old Alma, a Puerto Rican girl who lives with her family in the Bronx, learns to think for herself, making mistakes and finding solutions along the way.
listings.episode_description: Alma teaches Emi how to be like her, but now Emi won't stop imitating Alma; Alma tries to finish running the world's longest race.

listings.title: Molly of Denali
listings.description: The daily adventures of 10-year-old Alaska native Molly Mabray, her family, her dog Suki and her friends Tooey and Trini.
listings.episode_description: Trini wants to send her mom a care package but she is unable to find all of her favorite things; Trini and her dad find themselves without lights and heat during a blizzard.

listings.title: Lyla in the Loop
listings.episode_title: The Artist Formerly Known as Liana; Jamaica Day
listings.description: Seven-year-old Lyla and her close-knit family address everyday problems together in the big city.
listings.episode_description: Liana accidentally submits art that Stu made and feels guilty taking the credit for his work; Lyla and Luke perform an "Anansi" folktale puppet show.

listings.title: Arthur
listings.description: Bespectacled aardvark Arthur Read demonstrates to kids how to deal with such childhood traumas and challenges as homework, teachers and bullies. He also has to contend with his sisters, but loves playing with his friends: tomboy Francine, foodie and best pal Buster, supersmart Brain, rich girl Muffy and geography expert Sue Ellen.
listings.episode_description: D.W. is jealous when Emily gets the lead role in the preschool play; D.W. and Emily are not happy when they get stuck with blocks at playtime.

listings.title: Eyes on the Prize
listings.description: This landmark series, which first premiered in 1987, documents the history of the civil rights movement in America. Produced by Blackside, segments include the Montgomery bus boycott of 1954, school desegregation in 1957 Arkansas, the right-to-vote battle within Mississippi, the march from Selma to Montgomery, Ala., and the Voting Rights Act of 1965. The series has been honored with a George Foster Peabody Award, an International Documentary Award, Television Critics Association Award and numerous Emmy Awards.
listings.episode_description: Antidiscrimination legal rights are tested during the 1970s as Bostonians violently resist a federal court school desegregation order; Maynard Jackson becomes Atlanta's mayor.

listings.title: Eyes on the Prize

listings.episode_description: Riots explode in Miami's black community; Harold Washington is installed as Chicago's first black mayor.

listings.title: Girl Talk: A Local, USA Special
listings.description: Five girl debaters from a top ranked Massachusetts team navigate the world of high school debate.

listings.title: Stories From the Stage
listings.description: Theresa Okokon and Wes Hazard explore the art of storytelling.
listings.episode_description: A wardrobe mishap forces Carly Ciarrocchi to rethink what it really means to fit in; Adam Selbst's job takes a wild turn; Rory Scholl realizes fame isn't as glamorous as it seems.

listings.title: On Story
listings.description: A look inside the creative process of writers, creators and filmmakers.
listings.episode_description: Cord Jefferson discusses writing and directing his debut feature, "American Fiction."

listings.title: To the Contrary With Bonnie Erbé
listings.description: Award-winning journalist Bonnie Erbé hosts a round-table discussion of national and international politics, policies and events. Her guests are other female professionals, and its focus is on a woman's perspective. No topic is off-limits, from politics to working mothers to health care and anything else that affects women.
listings.episode_description: All-female news analysis of issues and policy affecting the U.S.

listings.title: Washington Week With The Atlantic
listings.description: Jeffrey Goldberg, editor in chief of The Atlantic, moderates a panel of journalists who report and provide analysis on the major stories emanating from the United States capital. Having first aired in 1967, "Washington Week" is the longest-running prime-time news and public affairs program on television. The series has been recognized for its journalism excellence with many honors, including a 2008 Peabody Award.
listings.episode_description: A panel of journalists provides reporting and analysis of the major stories emanating from the United States capital.

listings.title: The Open Mind
listings.description: Exploring civic life with Alexander Heffner.
listings.episode_description: Counterproliferation leader Emma Belcher discusses how to reverse the increasing probability of nuclear violence.

listings.title: Focus on Europe
listings.description: Stories and news from across Europe.
listings.episode_description: The end of USAID opens old wounds in Kosovo; European youth turn to the right; fashion combats the weariness of war in Ukraine; oil platform workers demand compensation in Norway; Istanbul's cat angel.

listings.title: Global Us
listings.description: A look at the biggest issues in the world today, including how people are living with opportunity and the ever-growing risks of globalization.
listings.episode_description: How a woman entrepreneur is greening the desert in Mali; empowering girls with education; clothes for people with disabilities; preserving heirloom potatoes with science.

listings.title: The Chavis Chronicles
listings.description: World leaders, politicians and cultural influencers offer insights into matters that impact the public.
listings.episode_description: Global environmentalist Amanda Costa, founder of Perifa Sustentavel.

listings.title: Laura Flanders & Friends
listings.episode_title: South Australia's Green Revolution: How Art & Policy Catalyze Climate Action
listings.description: Interviews and investigative reporting on the people and movements driving positive systemic change.
listings.episode_description: Rob Brookman, WOMADelaide; Susan Close, Deputy Premier, South Australia; Cassandre Joseph; Ruth Mackenzie; Caitlin Moore; Elizabeth Streb; Anote Tong; Bart Van Peel.

listings.title: Grantchester on Masterpiece
listings.description: In the Cambridgeshire village of Grantchester in the 1950s, gruff, down-to-earth police inspector Geordie Keating's methodical approach to police work complements the intuitive techniques of local vicar Sidney Chambers, and later the Rev. Will Davenport. Geordie forms an unlikely partnership with both men of the cloth, and as partners they bring different insights into the crimes they start to unravel, forming true friendships as they work together. Village life in Grantchester proves to be much livelier than its sleepy appearance might suggest, with intrigue and gossip swirling in the background of Geordie's investigations.
listings.episode_description: Will and Geordie are drawn into local politics when a councilor's death prompts a parish election; an allegation is made against Leonard.

listings.episode_description: An American airman's death leads to a challenging late shift for Will and Geordie; Leonard and Daniel reassess their relationship.

listings.title: Great Performances at the Met
listings.description: Opera lovers, rejoice! If you can't make it to New York to see a performance at the Metropolitan Opera, the next best thing to being there is to see one of its Saturday matinees broadcast on PBS. Originally aired as part of its "Great Performances" series, the programs got their own title in 2006. With operatic standards like "Aida," "The Barber of Seville" and "Turandot," and performances by some of opera's biggest names, including Reneé Flemming, Placido Domingo and Anna Netrebko, the series brings the best of modern opera into American homes.
listings.episode_description: Mezzo-soprano Emily D'Angelo portrays Jess, a fighter pilot whose unplanned pregnancy takes her out of the cockpit and lands her in Las Vegas, operating a drone.

listings.title: Great Performances
listings.episode_title: Audra McDonald at the London Palladium
listings.description: The performing arts anthology series brings best from the worlds of music and dance into viewers' living rooms. From classical music and opera to ballet and musical theater, cameras capture the stage performances of some of the best artists in the world.
listings.episode_description: Audra McDonald performs a repertoire of classic Broadway songs including "I Am What I Am," "I Could Have Danced All Night," "Will He Like Me?" and "Summertime."

listings.title: Consuelo Mack WealthTrack
listings.description: Financial journalist Consuelo Mack interviews some of the most trusted names in the investment business, along with what she terms "financial thought leaders" and big-name investors, all with an eye toward providing viewers with ways to build wealth and protect if over the long term. Mack and her guests deal with stocks, bonds, real estate and even art and collectibles as a means to building wealth. Each guest is asked to make a recommendation as to one stock that should be in a long-term portfolio, and she offers viewers her own Action Point, which is a step anyone can take to work toward building wealth.
listings.episode_description: Investment tips in stocks, bonds, real estate and collectibles.

listings.title: On the Record
listings.description: Interviews with key players in San Antonio politics, business, and community activism. Each week also includes a roundtable discussion with local journalists who keep a pulse on important issues impacting the city.
listings.episode_description: Interviews with key players in San Antonio politics, business, and community activism. Each week also includes a roundtable discussion with local journalists who keep a pulse on important issues impacting the city.

listings.title: UnReined
listings.description: American Israeli equestrian champion Nancy Zeitlin starts the first Palestinian equestrian team in Jericho.

listings.title: Nature
listings.description: Consistently stunning documentaries transport viewers to far-flung locations ranging from the torrid African plains to the chilly splendors of icy Antarctica. The show's primary focus is on animals and ecosystems around the world. A comic book based on the show, meant to be used an as educational tool for kids, was briefly distributed to museums and schools at no cost in the mid-2000s.
listings.episode_description: From elephants to termites, an entire community of creatures in Africa call the waterhole their home.

listings.title: Finding Your Roots With Henry Louis Gates, Jr.
listings.description: Educator Henry Louis Gates Jr. has hosted several PBS series that examine U.S. history. In "Finding Your Roots," the Harvard professor continues his quest to "get into the DNA of American culture." In each episode, celebrities view ancestral histories, sometimes learn of connections to famous/infamous people, discover secrets, and share the emotional experience with viewers. Analyzing genetic code, DNA diagnosticians trace bloodlines and occasionally debunk long-held beliefs.
listings.episode_description: Singers Ciara and Alanis Morissette examine their family histories.

listings.title: American Experience
listings.description: "American Experience" combines dramatic re-enactments with commentary by historians and authors to present an absorbing look at the personalities, events and resources that have had a profound impact on the shaping of America's past and present. Many of the program's documentaries have received major honors in the broadcasting community, including Emmy, Peabodys and duPont-Columbia University awards.
listings.episode_description: Scientist Rachel Carson's book "Silent Spring" and other writings advance the global environmental movement.
